# Diffusion-Models-From-Zero-to-One
This document was translated by AI.
Understanding diffusion models from zero to one: starting from the noising formula of a single pixel channel, step by step, we understand how diffusion models learn to denoise and ultimately generate images from random noise.

# Diffusion

Forward noising process
Suppose we have a color image, and the value of one color channel of one pixel is $`x_0`$. Then the noising process is as follows:

```math
x_1
=
\sqrt{1-\beta_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\epsilon_1
```

Here, $`\epsilon_1`$ is the noise value, sampled from a standard Gaussian random variable $`\varepsilon\sim\mathcal N(0,1)`$. The parameter $`\beta_1`$ is the manually chosen noise strength for the first noising step, usually satisfying $`0<\beta<1`$. Written in random-variable form, we have:

```math
X_1
=
\sqrt{1-\beta_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\varepsilon_1
```

The general form of the noising process is:

```math
X_t
=
\sqrt{1-\beta_t}x_{t-1}
+
\sqrt{\beta_t}\varepsilon_t,\quad \varepsilon_t \sim \mathcal N(0,1)
```

Strictly speaking, $`X_t`$ follows a conditional Gaussian distribution:

```math
\mathcal L\left(X_t\mid X_{t-1}=x_{t-1},X_0=x_0\right)
=\mathcal N
\left(
\sqrt{1-\beta_t}x_{t-1},
\beta_t
\right)
```

Because $`X_t`$ only depends on the result from the previous timestep, the noising process is essentially a Markov process. Therefore, the condition $`X_0=x_0`$ can be omitted:

```math
\mathcal{L}\left(X_t\mid X_{t-1}=x_{t-1}\right)
=
\mathcal N
\left(
\sqrt{1-\beta_t}x_{t-1},
\beta_t
\right)
```

This can be further abbreviated as:

```math
\mathcal L (X_t\mid x_{t-1})
=
\mathcal N
\left(
\sqrt{1-\beta_t}x_{t-1},
\beta_t
\right)
```

We use $`q_t`$ to denote the conditional probability density, so:

```math
q_t(x_t\mid x_{t-1})
=
\mathcal N
\left(
x_t;
\sqrt{1-\beta_t}x_{t-1},
\beta_t
\right)
```

Define:

```math
\begin{gathered}
\alpha_t\doteq 1-\beta_t,\quad 1>\alpha_t>0
\\\bar{\alpha}_t \doteq \prod_{i=1}^t \alpha_i,\quad 1>\bar\alpha_t>0
\end{gathered}
```

If we do not specify $`x_{t-1}`$, the recursive formula can be written as:

```math
X_t
=
\sqrt{\alpha_t}X_{t-1}
+
\sqrt{1-\alpha_t}\varepsilon_t
```

Then, conditioned on $`X_0=x_0`$, we have:

```math
\begin{aligned}
X_t
&= \sqrt{\alpha_t} X_{t-1} + \sqrt{1 - \alpha_t} \varepsilon_t \\
&= \sqrt{\alpha_t}
\left(
\sqrt{\alpha_{t-1}} X_{t-2}
+
\sqrt{1 - \alpha_{t-1}} \varepsilon_{t-1}
\right)
+
\sqrt{1 - \alpha_t} \varepsilon_t \\
&= \sqrt{\alpha_t \alpha_{t-1}} X_{t-2}
+
\sqrt{\alpha_t (1 - \alpha_{t-1})} \varepsilon_{t-1}
+
\sqrt{1 - \alpha_t} \varepsilon_t \\
&\vdots \\
&= \sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_t} x_0
+
\sum_{i=1}^{t-1}
\left(
\sqrt{\prod_{j=i+1}^{t} \alpha_j}
\sqrt{1 - \alpha_i}
\varepsilon_i
\right)
+
\sqrt{1 - \alpha_t} \varepsilon_t
\\&=\sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_t} x_0
+
\sum_{i=1}^{t}
\left(
\sqrt{\prod_{j=i+1}^{t} \alpha_j}
\sqrt{1 - \alpha_i}
\varepsilon_i
\right),\quad \left(\text{by convention, the empty product }\sqrt{\prod_{j=t+1}^{t}\alpha_j}=1\right)
\end{aligned}
```

We can see that, conditioned on $`X_0=x_0`$, the random variable $`X_t`$ is equivalent to a linear combination of several mutually independent Gaussian random variables $`\varepsilon_1,\varepsilon_2,\cdots,\varepsilon_t`$. Since a linear combination of independent Gaussian variables is still Gaussian, $`X_t`$ also follows a Gaussian distribution conditioned on $`X_0=x_0`$. For any two random variables X and Y, $`\mathrm{Var}(X + Y) = \mathrm{Var}(X) + \mathrm{Var}(Y) + 2\mathrm{Cov}(X, Y)`$. Therefore, for any $`i\neq j`$, $`\mathrm{Var}(\varepsilon_i + \varepsilon_j) = \mathrm{Var}(\varepsilon_i) + \mathrm{Var}(\varepsilon_j) + 2\mathrm{Cov}(\varepsilon_i, \varepsilon_j)=\mathrm{Var}(\varepsilon_i) + \mathrm{Var}(\varepsilon_j)`$. Thus:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\mathrm{Var}
\left(
X_t\mid x_0
\right)
&=
\sum_{i=1}^{t-1}
\mathrm{Var}
\left(
\sqrt{\prod_{j=i+1}^{t}\alpha_j}
\sqrt{1-\alpha_i}
\varepsilon_i
\right)
+
\mathrm{Var}
\left(
\sqrt{1-\alpha_t}\varepsilon_t
\right)
\\
&=
\sum_{i=1}^{t-1}
\left(
\prod_{j=i+1}^{t}\alpha_j
\right)
(1-\alpha_i)
+
(1-\alpha_t)
\\
&=
\sum_{i=1}^{t-1}
\left(
\prod_{j=i+1}^{t}\alpha_j
-
\prod_{j=i}^{t}\alpha_j
\right)
+
(1-\alpha_t)
\\
&=
\left(
\prod_{j=2}^{t}\alpha_j
-
\prod_{j=1}^{t}\alpha_j
\right)
+
\left(
\prod_{j=3}^{t}\alpha_j
-
\prod_{j=2}^{t}\alpha_j
\right)
+
\cdots
+
\left(
\prod_{j=t}^{t}\alpha_j
-
\prod_{j=t-1}^{t}\alpha_j
\right)
+
1-\alpha_t
\\
&=
-\prod_{j=1}^{t}\alpha_j
+
\prod_{j=t}^{t}\alpha_j
+
1-\alpha_t
\\
&=
-\bar{\alpha}_t
+
\alpha_t
+
1-\alpha_t
\\
&=
1-\bar{\alpha}_t .
\end{aligned}
```

Therefore, we can directly write down the conditional distribution for sampling $`X_t`$ from $`x_0`$:

```math
\mathcal L (X_t\mid x_0)
=
\mathcal N
\left(
\sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_t}x_0,
1-\bar{\alpha}_t
\right)
```

Thus:

```math
X_t= \sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0
+
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\bar\varepsilon_t,\quad \bar\varepsilon_t\sim \mathcal  N(0,1)
```

Here, $`\bar\varepsilon_t`$ is used to distinguish it from the local noise $`\varepsilon_t`$ in the recursive formula. Although both random variables follow a standard normal distribution, they are different random variables. Their relationship is:

```math
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\bar\varepsilon_t=\sum_{i=1}^{t}
\left(
\sqrt{\prod_{j=i+1}^{t} \alpha_j}
\sqrt{1 - \alpha_i}
\varepsilon_i
\right),\quad \left(\text{by convention, the empty product }\sqrt{\prod_{j=t+1}^{t}\alpha_j}=1\right)
```

The conditional probability density function is:
$`q_t(x_t\mid x_0)=\mathcal{N}(x_t;\sqrt{\bar \alpha_t}x_{0},(1-\bar \alpha_t))`$
The essential meaning of direct sampling being equivalent to step-by-step sampling is not that the value of $`x_t`$ obtained by direct sampling is exactly the same as the value obtained by step-by-step sampling. Rather, after infinitely many samples, the distributions formed by $`x_t`$ from the two sampling methods are the same. When we choose an appropriate $`\beta`$ sequence such that $`\lim_{t\to\infty}\bar \alpha_t=\prod_{i=1}^t \alpha_i=\prod_{i=1}^t (1-\beta_i)=0`$, then when T is sufficiently large, we have:
$`q_T(x_T\mid x_0)\approx\mathcal{N}(x_T;0,1)`$.
Generation process
Once $`x_0`$ is given, the analytical expressions for all later random variables $`X_1,X_2,\cdots,X_T`$ can be written directly. If we can construct a neural network $`\theta`$ to learn a distribution $`\mathcal L(X_{t-1}\mid x_t)`$ from $`x_t`$ and $`t`$, then we can use this distribution to reverse the noising process. By repeating this reverse process, we can eventually obtain the distribution of $`X_0`$, which is the data distribution of the training samples $`x_0`$. A natural question may arise: from $`x_t`$ to $`x_0`$, the intermediate $`x_{t-1}`$ depends on $`x_t`$, and the whole path is random. How can we ensure that $`x_T`$ generates a deterministic $`x_0`$? In fact, the generation process introduced here does not generate a fixed image deterministically; it generates a distribution. That is, we cannot recover a specific deterministic $`x_0`$ from $`x_T`$, but we can train the model so that samples generated from $`x_T`$ follow the same distribution as the training data $`x_0`$. Before continuing, let us briefly introduce joint probability densities. For two continuous random variables X and Y, if they are independent, their joint probability density is:
$`f_{X,Y}(x,y)=f_X(x)\cdot f_Y(y)`$
When the two random variables are not independent, their joint probability density function is:
$`f_{X,Y}(x,y)=f_X(x)\cdot f_{Y\mid X}(y\mid x)=f_Y(y)\cdot f_{X\mid Y}(x\mid y)`$
Given $`x_0`$, we combine the random variables corresponding to all later results:

```math
X_{1:T}
\doteq
\begin{pmatrix}
X_1\\
X_2\\
\vdots\\
X_T
\end{pmatrix}
```

$`X_{1:T}`$ can also be called a random vector. A necessary and sufficient condition for $`X,Y`$ to form a jointly Gaussian distribution, or multivariate Gaussian distribution, is that every nonzero linear combination $`aX+bY`$ must be Gaussian or degenerate Gaussian. Here, a nonzero linear combination means that $`a,b`$ are not both zero; a degenerate Gaussian means $`\mathcal N(c,0),c\in \mathbb R`$. Since the linear combinations $`a=1,b=0`$ and $`a=0,b=1`$ must also be Gaussian or degenerate Gaussian, this also requires $`X,Y`$ themselves to each be Gaussian or degenerate Gaussian. In addition, the conditional distribution of jointly Gaussian random variables is still Gaussian; that is, $`X\mid Y=y`$ must also follow a Gaussian distribution. A random vector following a multivariate Gaussian distribution can be written as:

```math
\begin{pmatrix}
X\\
Y
\end{pmatrix}
\sim
\mathcal N
\left(
\mu,
\Sigma
\right),\mu=\begin{pmatrix}
\mu_X\\
\mu_Y
\end{pmatrix},\Sigma
=
\begin{pmatrix}
\mathrm{Var}(X) & \mathrm{Cov}(X,Y)\\
\mathrm{Cov}(Y,X) & \mathrm{Var}(Y)
\end{pmatrix}
```

Here, $`\mu`$ denotes the mean vector, and $`\Sigma`$ denotes the covariance matrix of X and Y. Suppose a certain generation process correctly generates $`x_0`$ step by step, with sampled values $`x_{T},\cdots,x_{1},x_0`$. We denote the probability density of the generation process as:
$`p_{t-1}(x_{t-1}\mid x_t)`$
Then the joint probability density function of this sampled sequence is:

```math
\begin{aligned}
p_{0:T} (x_{0:T})&=p_T(x_T) p_{T-1}(x_{T-1} \mid x_T) p_{T-2}(x_{T-2} \mid x_{T}, x_{T-1}) \cdots p_{0}(x_0 \mid x_T, \dots, x_{1})
\\&=p_T(x_T) p_{T-1}(x_{T-1} \mid x_T) p_{T-2}(x_{T-2} \mid  x_{T-1}) \cdots p_{0}(x_0 \mid x_{1})\qquad \text{(by the Markov property)}
\\&= p_T(x_T) \prod_{t=1}^T p_{t-1}(x_{t-1} \mid x_t)
\end{aligned}
```

In standard DDPM, the prior distribution of $`X_T`$ is fixed as a standard Gaussian:
$`p_T(x_T)=\mathcal{N}(x_T;0,1)`$
Note that the path $`x_T,x_{T-1},\cdots,x_{0}`$ above is only one path from $`x_T`$ to $`x_0`$. There are infinitely many other paths leading to $`x_0`$. Therefore, the probability density of eventually generating $`x_0`$ should be obtained by integrating over all random variables in the joint distribution except $`x_0`$. The result is still the marginal probability density function of $`x_0`$:
$`p_0(x_0)=\int p_{0:T}(x_{1:T},x_0) \, dx_{1:T}`$
The most direct training objective is to maximize $`p_0(x_0)`$. To simplify the computation, this is usually converted into maximizing $`\log p_0(x_0)`$. However, directly optimizing $`\log p_0(x_0)`$ is difficult. Therefore, we introduce the known and tractable forward-process distribution $`q(x_{1:T}\mid x_0)`$ and simplify the above integral using importance sampling:

```math
\begin{aligned}
p_0(x_0) &= \int p_{0:T}(x_{0:T}) \, dx_{1:T}
\\&= \int q_{1:T}(x_{1:T} \mid x_0) \cdot \frac{p_{0:T}(x_{1:T},x_0)}{q_{1:T}(x_{1:T} \mid x_0)} \, dx_{1:T}
\\&=\mathbb{E}_{X_{1:T}\sim Q_{1:T}(\cdot\mid x_0)} \left[ \frac{p_{0:T}(x_0,X_{1:T})}{q_{1:T}(X_{1:T} \mid x_0)} \right],\quad p_{0:T}(x_0,X_{1:T})=p_T(X_T) \prod_{t=2}^T p_{t-1}(X_{t-1} \mid X_t)p_0(x_{0} \mid X_1)
\end{aligned}
```

At this point, $`X_1,X_2,\cdots,X_T`$ denotes joint random variables following the forward conditional distribution. Let $`X`$ be a random variable and $`f(x)`$ be its probability density function. If we substitute $`Y\doteq X_1+X_2`$ into the probability density function $`f(x)`$, we obtain another random variable $`f(Y)`$. Therefore, $`p_{0:T}(x_0,X_{1:T}),q_{1:T}(X_{1:T} \mid x_0),p(X_T),p_{t-1}(X_{t-1} \mid X_t),p_0(x_{0} \mid X_1)`$ are all random variables. Here, $`X_{1:T}\sim Q_{1:T}(\cdot\mid x_0)`$ means that $`X_1,X_{2},\cdots,X_T`$ follows the joint conditional distribution $`Q_{1:T}(\cdot\mid x_0)`$; each random variable in $`X_{1:T}`$ also follows a marginal conditional distribution $`Q_t(\cdot\mid x_0)`$. By Jensen's inequality, for any random variable $`X`$ and convex function $`f`$, we have $`f(\mathbb E[X])\le \mathbb E[f(X)]`$; if $`f`$ is concave, the inequality is reversed, so $`f(\mathbb E[X])\ge \mathbb E[f(X)]`$. Since log is concave, we have $`\log(\mathbb E[X])\ge \mathbb E[\log(X)]`$. Define:

```math
Z
\doteq
\frac{
p_{0:T}(x_0,X_{1:T})
}{
q_{1:T}(X_{1:T}\mid x_0)
}
```

Then:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\log p_0(x_0)
&=
\log
\mathbb{E}_{X_{1:T}\sim Q_{1:T}(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
\frac{
p_{0:T}(x_0,X_{1:T})
}{
q_{1:T}(X_{1:T}\mid x_0)
}
\right]
\\
&\geq
\mathbb{E}_{X_{1:T}\sim Q_{1:T}(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
\log
\frac{
p_{0:T}(x_0,X_{1:T})
}{
q_{1:T}(X_{1:T}\mid x_0)
