Now explain the chain rule of conditional probability. Let $`A,B,C`$ be arbitrary random variables. Their joint probability density is:
$`q(A,B,C)=q(C)q(B\mid C)q(A\mid B,C)`$
Essentially, even if there is a dependency order among these random variables, for example A is formed from B and B is formed from C, this does not mean that the above expression can only be expanded in that order. In fact, we can expand it in any order, for example:
$`q(A,B,C)=q(A)q(B\mid A)q(C\mid A,B)`$
By the chain rule of conditional probability, we can decompose $`q_{1:T}(X_{1:T}\mid x_0)`$ in any order and therefore write it in another form:

```math
\begin{aligned}
q_{1:T}(X_{1:T}\mid x_0)
&=
q_T(X_T\mid x_0)
q_{T-1}(X_{T-1}\mid X_T,x_0)
q_{T-2}(X_{T-2}\mid X_{T-1},X_T,x_0)\cdots
q_1(X_1\mid X_2,X_3,\cdots,X_T,x_0)
\\&=q_T(X_T\mid x_0)
q_{T-1}(X_{T-1}\mid X_T,x_0)
q_{T-2}(X_{T-2}\mid X_{T-1},x_0)
\cdots
q_1(X_1\mid X_2,x_0)\quad \text{(Markov form)}
\\&=q_T(X_T\mid x_0)
\prod_{t=2}^{T}
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)
\end{aligned}
```

