\mathbb{E}_{X_{t-1}\sim Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)}
\left[
\log p_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t)
-
\log q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)
\right]
\Bigg]
\end{aligned}
```

By the definition of KL divergence:

```math
\begin{aligned}
&D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)
\|
P_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t)
\right)
\\
&=
\mathbb{E}_{X_{t-1}\sim Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)}
\left[
\log q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)
-
\log p_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t)
\right]
\end{aligned}
```

Substituting this back into the inner expectation gives:

```math
\begin{aligned}
-
\mathbb{E}_{X_t\sim Q_t(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)
\|
P_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t)
\right)
\right]
\end{aligned}
```

Therefore, term B is:

```math
\begin{aligned}
-
\sum_{t=2}^{T}
\mathbb{E}_{X_t\sim Q_t(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)
\|
P_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t)
\right)
\right]
\end{aligned}
```

Next, we handle term C. Similarly, after changing the order of integration, it is equivalent to computing the expectation using only the marginal conditional distribution of $`X_1\mid x_0`$:

```math
C=\mathbb{E}_{X_{1:T}\sim Q_{1:T}(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
\log p_0(x_0\mid X_1)
\right]
=
\mathbb{E}_{X_1\sim Q_1(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
\log p_0(x_0\mid X_1)
\right]
```

Combining the results above gives the KL decomposition of the ELBO:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{ELBO}}(x_0)
&=
-
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_T(\cdot\mid x_0)
\|
P_T
\right)
\\
&\quad
-
\sum_{t=2}^{T}
\mathbb{E}_{X_t\sim Q_t(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)
\|
P_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t)
\right)
\right]
\\
&\quad
+
\mathbb{E}_{X_1\sim Q_1(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
\log p_0(x_0\mid X_1)
\right]
\end{aligned}
```

Since:
$`\log p_0(x_0)\ge\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{ELBO}}(x_0)`$
Then:
$`-\log p_0(x_0)\le-\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{ELBO}}(x_0)`$
Define:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{VLB}}(x_0)
\doteq
-
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{ELBO}}(x_0)&=
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_T(\cdot\mid x_0)
\|
P_T
\right)
\\
&\quad
+
\sum_{t=2}^{T}
\mathbb{E}_{X_t\sim Q_t(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)
\|
P_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t)
\right)
\right]
\\
&\quad
-
\mathbb{E}_{X_1\sim Q_1(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
\log p_0(x_0\mid X_1)
\right]
\end{aligned}
```

Therefore, in training, we usually minimize $`\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{VLB}}(x_0)`$ to maximize the lower bound of $`\log p_0(x_0)`$. Let:

```math
\begin{aligned}
L_0
&=
-
\mathbb E_{X_1\sim Q_1(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
\log p_0(x_0\mid X_1)
\right]
\\L_{t-1}
&=
\mathbb E_{X_t\sim Q_t(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)
\|
P_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t)
\right)
\right],
\qquad
t=2,\dots,T
\\L_T
&=
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_T(\cdot\mid x_0)
\|
P_T
\right),\quad P_T=\mathcal N(0,1)
\end{aligned}
```

Then:

```math
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{VLB}}
=
L_T
+
\sum_{t=2}^{T}L_{t-1}
+
L_0
```

First, look at:

```math
L_{t-1}=\mathbb{E}_{X_t\sim Q_t(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)
\|
P_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t)
\right)
\right]
```

To compute the above expression, we need to solve for $`q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)`$. By Bayes’ formula:

```math
\begin{aligned}
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)
=
\frac{
q_t(X_t\mid X_{t-1},x_0)
\,
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid x_0)
}{
q_t(X_t\mid x_0)
}
&\\=\frac{
q_t(X_t\mid X_{t-1})
\,
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid x_0)
}{
q_t(X_t\mid x_0)
}
\end{aligned}
```

Because the denominator does not contain $`X_{t-1}`$, and $`q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)`$ is a function of $`X_{t-1}`$, we have:

```math
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)
=C
q_t(X_t\mid X_{t-1})
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid x_0)
```

Since:

```math
\begin{aligned}
q_t(X_t\mid X_{t-1})
&=
\mathcal N
\left(
X_t;
\sqrt{\alpha_t}X_{t-1},
\beta_t
\right)
\\
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid x_0)
&=
\mathcal N
\left(
X_{t-1};
\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}x_0,
1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}
\right)
\end{aligned}
```

The probability density function of a Gaussian distribution $`X\sim\mathcal N(\mu,\sigma^2)`$ is:

```math
\mathcal N(x;\mu,\sigma^2)
=
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}}
\exp
\left(
-\frac{(x-\mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}
\right)
```

Here, $`\exp(A)=e^A`$. For the conditional Gaussian distribution

```math
\mathcal L(Y\mid X=x)
=
\mathcal N
\left(
\mu(x),
\sigma^2(x)
\right)
```

the probability density function is:

```math
p(y\mid x)
=
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2(x)}}
\exp
\left(
-
\frac{
\left(
y-\mu(x)
\right)^2
}{
2\sigma^2(x)
}
\right)
```

Then:

```math
\begin{gathered}
q_t(X_t \mid X_{t-1})
= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\beta_t}}
\exp\left(
    -\frac{\bigl(X_t - \sqrt{\alpha_t}\,X_{t-1}\bigr)^2}{2\beta_t}
\right)
\\
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1} \mid x_0)
= \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi(1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1})}}
\exp\left(
    -\frac{\bigl(X_{t-1} - \sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}\,x_0\bigr)^2}{2(1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1})}
\right)
\end{gathered}
```

Because $`1>\beta_t>0`$ and $`1>\bar\alpha_t>0`$, we have:

```math
\begin{aligned}
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)
&=C
\exp
\left(
-\frac{
\left(
X_t-\sqrt{\alpha_t}X_{t-1}
\right)^2
}{
2\beta_t
}
\right)
\\
&\quad\times
\exp
\left(
-\frac{
\left(
X_{t-1}-\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}x_0
\right)^2
}{
2(1-\bar\alpha_{t-1})
}
\right)
\\
&=C
\exp
\left(
-\frac{
\left(
X_t-\sqrt{\alpha_t}X_{t-1}
\right)^2
}{
2\beta_t
}
-
\frac{
\left(
X_{t-1}-\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}x_0
\right)^2
}{
2(1-\bar\alpha_{t-1})
}
\right)
\end{aligned}
```

Expand the squared terms:

```math
\begin{gathered}
\left(
X_t-\sqrt{\alpha_t}X_{t-1}
\right)^2
=
\alpha_t X_{t-1}^2
-
2\sqrt{\alpha_t}X_t X_{t-1}
+
X_t^2
\\
\left(
X_{t-1}-\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}x_0
\right)^2
=
X_{t-1}^2
-
2\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}x_0 X_{t-1}
+
\bar\alpha_{t-1}x_0^2
\end{gathered}
```

Here, only $`X_{t-1}`$ is the variable, so all terms that do not contain $`X_{t-1}`$ can be merged into a constant term. The exponent is therefore:

```math
\begin{aligned}
-\frac{\left(X_t-\sqrt{\alpha_t}X_{t-1}\right)^2}{2\beta_t}
-\frac{\left(X_{t-1}-\sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}x_0\right)^2}{2(1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1})} &= -\frac{1}{2\beta_t}\bigl(\alpha_t X_{t-1}^2 - 2\sqrt{\alpha_t}X_t X_{t-1} + X_t^2\bigr) \\
&\qquad -\frac{1}{2(1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1})}\bigl(X_{t-1}^2 - 2\sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}x_0 X_{t-1} + \bar{\alpha}_{t-1}x_0^2\bigr) \\[4pt]
&= -\frac{1}{2}\Biggl[
\left(\frac{\alpha_t}{\beta_t} + \frac{1}{1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}\right)X_{t-1}^2 \\
&\qquad -2\left(\frac{\sqrt{\alpha_t}\,X_t}{\beta_t} + \frac{\sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}\,x_0}{1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}\right)X_{t-1} + \left(\frac{X_t^2}{\beta_t} + \frac{\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}x_0^2}{1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}\right)\Biggr]
\\&= -\frac{1}{2}\Biggl[
\left(\frac{\alpha_t}{\beta_t} + \frac{1}{1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}\right)X_{t-1}^2-2\left(\frac{\sqrt{\alpha_t}\,X_t}{\beta_t} + \frac{\sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}\,x_0}{1-\bar{\alpha}_{t-1}}\right)X_{t-1} + \mathrm{const}\Biggr]
\end{aligned}
```

Because conditioned on $`X_0=x_0`$, $`X_{t-1},X_t`$ can form a multivariate Gaussian distribution, as we already established the joint distribution $`X_{1:T}`$ earlier, $`X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0`$ must also follow a Gaussian distribution. Thus:

```math
\begin{aligned}
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)&=\mathcal N\left(X_{t-1}; \tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0), \tilde\beta_t \right)
\\&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\tilde\beta_t}}\mathrm{exp}\left(-\frac{
\left(
X_{t-1}-\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)
\right)^2
}{
2\tilde\beta_t
}\right)
\end{aligned}
```

The reason we write $`\tilde\beta_t`$ instead of $`\tilde\beta_t(X_t,x_0)`$ is that the following derivation will show that $`\tilde\beta_t`$ is a constant independent of the conditions $`x_0,X_t`$. Omitting the arguments here is only for simplicity; writing $`\tilde\beta_t(X_t,x_0)`$ would not affect the derivation. Expanding the exponent gives:

```math
-\frac{
\left(
X_{t-1}-\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)
\right)^2
}{
2\tilde\beta_t
}=-\frac12
\left[
\frac{1}{\tilde\beta_t}X_{t-1}^2
-
2\frac{\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)}{\tilde\beta_t}X_{t-1}
\right]
+
\mathrm{const}
```

Here, $`\tilde\beta_t`$ is different from the manually specified $`\beta`$ in the forward process. This $`\tilde\beta_t`$ denotes the variance of $`X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0`$. Comparing coefficients gives:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\frac{1}{\tilde\beta_t}
&=
\frac{\alpha_t}{\beta_t}
+
\frac{1}{1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}}=
\frac{
\alpha_t(1-\bar\alpha_{t-1})+\beta_t
}{
\beta_t(1-\bar\alpha_{t-1})
}
\\&=\frac{\alpha_t-\alpha_t\bar\alpha_{t-1}+1-\alpha_t}{\beta_t(1-\bar\alpha_{t-1})}=\frac{1-\alpha_t\bar\alpha_{t-1}}{\beta_t(1-\bar\alpha_{t-1})},\quad(\beta_t=1-\alpha_t)
\\&=\frac{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}{
\beta_t(1-\bar\alpha_{t-1})
},\quad(\bar\alpha_t=\alpha_t\bar\alpha_{t-1})
\end{aligned}
```

Therefore:

```math
\tilde\beta_t
=
\frac{
1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
\beta_t
```

We can see that $`\tilde\beta_t`$ is a constant independent of the conditions $`x_0,X_t`$. Comparing coefficients again gives:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)}{\tilde\beta_t}
&=
\frac{\sqrt{\alpha_t}}{\beta_t}X_t
+
\frac{\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}}{1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}}x_0
\\
\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)
&=
\tilde\beta_t
\left(
\frac{\sqrt{\alpha_t}}{\beta_t}X_t
+
\frac{\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}}{1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}}x_0
\right)
\end{aligned}
```

Substituting $`\tilde\beta_t`$ gives:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)
&=
\frac{
1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
\beta_t
\left(
\frac{\sqrt{\alpha_t}}{\beta_t}X_t
+
\frac{\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}}{1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}}x_0
\right)
\\
&=
\frac{
\sqrt{\alpha_t}(1-\bar\alpha_{t-1})
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
X_t
+
\frac{
\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}\beta_t
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
x_0
\end{aligned}
```

Then:

```math
\begin{aligned}
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)&=\mathcal N\left(X_{t-1}; \frac{
\sqrt{\alpha_t}(1-\bar\alpha_{t-1})
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
X_t
+
\frac{
\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}\beta_t
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
x_0, \frac{
1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
\beta_t \right)
\end{aligned}
```

Because:

```math
\mathcal L (X_t\mid x_0)
=
\mathcal N
\left(
\sqrt{\bar{\alpha}_t}x_0,
1-\bar{\alpha}_t
\right)
```

That is, conditioned on $`X_0=x_0`$, we have:

```math
X_t= \sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0
+
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\bar\varepsilon_t,\quad \bar\varepsilon_t\sim \mathcal  N(0,1)
```

Rearranging gives:

```math
x_0
=
\frac{
X_t-\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\varepsilon_t
}{
\sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}
}
```

This may raise a question: why does an operation involving two random variables eventually produce a constant $`x_0`$? The reason is that $`X_t`$ and $`\varepsilon_t`$ are not independent random variables. $`X_t`$ is constructed from $`x_0`$ and $`\varepsilon_t`$, so during the operation between $`X_t`$ and $`\varepsilon_t`$, the random parts cancel out, leaving only the constant. Substituting this into $`\tilde\mu_t`$ gives:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)
&=
\frac{
\sqrt{\bar\alpha_{t-1}}\beta_t
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
\cdot
\frac{
X_t-\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\varepsilon_t
}{
\sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}
}
+
\frac{
\sqrt{\alpha_t}(1-\bar\alpha_{t-1})
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
X_t
\\
&=
\frac{1}{\sqrt{\alpha_t}}
\left(
X_t
-
\frac{\beta_t}{\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}}\varepsilon_t
\right)
\end{aligned}
```

Even though $`x_0`$ no longer appears explicitly here, it is still implicitly contained in $`X_t`$, so for consistency of notation we still include it among the arguments. Therefore, we obtain:

```math
\begin{aligned}
q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)&=\mathcal N\left(X_{t-1}; \frac{1}{\sqrt{\alpha_t}}
\left(
X_t
-
\frac{\beta_t}{\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}}\varepsilon_t
\right), \frac{
1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
\beta_t \right)
\end{aligned}
```

During training, we know $`x_0`$ and the sampled noise $`\varepsilon_t`$, so we can compute the true posterior $`q_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)`$. During generation, however, we only have $`X_t`$; by using $`X_T`$, one can determine $`X_{T-1}`$, and so on until finally obtaining $`X_0`$. We do not have $`x_0`$, and we do not know the true noise $`\varepsilon_t`$. Therefore, we need to use the neural-network-defined distribution $`p_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t)`$ to approximate the true posterior $`q_{t-1}(x_{t-1}\mid X_t,x_0)`$ that can be computed during training. In this fitting process, the only quantity we need to know is $`\varepsilon_t`$, so we only need the neural network $`\theta`$ to learn the noise $`\varepsilon_\theta(X_t,t)`$. Thus, we obtain:

```math
\begin{aligned}
p_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t)&=\mathcal{N}\left( X_{t-1};
\mu_\theta(X_t,t), \frac{
1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
\beta_t \right)
\\\mu_\theta(X_t,t)&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\alpha_t}}
\left(
X_t
-
\frac{\beta_t}{\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}}
\varepsilon_\theta(X_t,t)
\right)
\end{aligned}
```

In practice, however, we often do not restrict the variance to

```math
\frac{
1-\bar\alpha_{t-1}
}{
1-\bar\alpha_t
}
\beta_t
```

, but instead set it as a freely chosen time-dependent constant. Therefore, to keep the form more general, we write the variance as $`\sigma^2_t`$:

```math
p_{t-1}(X_{t-1}\mid X_t)=\mathcal{N}\left( X_{t-1};
\mu_\theta(X_t,t), \sigma^2_t\right)
```

The KL divergence between two Gaussian distributions is:

```math
\begin{aligned}
&\quad D_{\mathrm{KL}}\left(\mathcal{N}(\mu_1,\sigma_1^2) \,\|\, \mathcal{N}(\mu_2,\sigma_2^2)\right) \\
&= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma_1} \exp\!\left(-\frac{(x-\mu_1)^2}{2\sigma_1^2}\right)
\log\frac{
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma_1} \exp\!\left(-\frac{(x-\mu_1)^2}{2\sigma_1^2}\right)
}{
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma_2} \exp\!\left(-\frac{(x-\mu_2)^2}{2\sigma_2^2}\right)
} \,dx \\
&= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty}
\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma_1} \exp\!\left(-\frac{(x-\mu_1)^2}{2\sigma_1^2}\right)
\left[ \log\frac{\sigma_2}{\sigma_1} - \frac{(x-\mu_1)^2}{2\sigma_1^2} + \frac{(x-\mu_2)^2}{2\sigma_2^2} \right] dx \\
&= \log\frac{\sigma_2}{\sigma_1} \underbrace{\int p(x)dx}_{=1}
- \frac{1}{2\sigma_1^2} \underbrace{\int (x-\mu_1)^2 p(x)dx}_{=\sigma_1^2}
+ \frac{1}{2\sigma_2^2} \underbrace{\int (x-\mu_2)^2 p(x)dx}_{\mathbb{E}_p[(x-\mu_2)^2]} \\
&= \log\frac{\sigma_2}{\sigma_1} - \frac12
+ \frac{1}{2\sigma_2^2} \mathbb{E}_p\big[(x-\mu_2)^2\big] \\
&= \log\frac{\sigma_2}{\sigma_1} - \frac12
+ \frac{1}{2\sigma_2^2} \Big( \mathbb{E}_p\big[((x-\mu_1)+(\mu_1-\mu_2))^2\big] \Big) \\
&= \log\frac{\sigma_2}{\sigma_1} - \frac12
+ \frac{1}{2\sigma_2^2} \Big( \mathbb{E}_p[(x-\mu_1)^2] + 2(\mu_1-\mu_2)\underbrace{\mathbb{E}_p[x-\mu_1]}_{=0} + (\mu_1-\mu_2)^2 \Big) \\
&= \log\frac{\sigma_2}{\sigma_1} - \frac12
+ \frac{1}{2\sigma_2^2} \big( \sigma_1^2 + (\mu_1-\mu_2)^2 \big) \\
&= \log\frac{\sigma_2}{\sigma_1} + \frac{\sigma_1^2 + (\mu_1-\mu_2)^2}{2\sigma_2^2} - \frac12
\end{aligned}
```

At this point, we can finally write the analytic form of the KL divergence in $`L_{t-1}`$:

```math
\begin{aligned}
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)
\|
P_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t)
\right)
&=
\log
\frac{\sigma_t}{\sqrt{\tilde\beta_t}}
+
\frac{
\tilde\beta_t
+
\left(
\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)-\mu_\theta(X_t,t)
\right)^2
}{
2\sigma_t^2
}
-\frac12
\end{aligned}
```

where:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)-\mu_\theta(X_t,t)
&=
\frac{1}{\sqrt{\alpha_t}}
\left(
-\frac{\beta_t}{\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}}\varepsilon_t
+
\frac{\beta_t}{\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}}\varepsilon_\theta(X_t,t)
\right)
\\
&=
\frac{\beta_t}{
\sqrt{\alpha_t}\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}
}
\left(
\varepsilon_\theta(X_t,t)-\varepsilon_t
\right)
\end{aligned}
```

Therefore:

```math
\left(
\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)-\mu_\theta(X_t,t)
\right)^2
=
\frac{
\beta_t^2
}{
\alpha_t(1-\bar\alpha_t)
}
\left(
\varepsilon_t-\varepsilon_\theta(X_t,t)
\right)^2
```

Thus:

```math
\frac{
\left(
\tilde\mu_t(X_t,x_0)-\mu_\theta(X_t,t)
\right)^2
}{
2\sigma_t^2
}
=
\frac{
\beta_t^2
}{
2\sigma_t^2\alpha_t(1-\bar\alpha_t)
}
\left(
\varepsilon_t-\varepsilon_\theta(X_t,t)
\right)^2
```

Thus:

```math
\begin{aligned}
L_{t-1}
&=
\mathbb E_{X_t\sim Q_t(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t,x_0)
\|
P_{t-1}(\cdot\mid X_t)
\right)
\right]
\\
&=
\mathbb E_{\varepsilon_t\sim\mathcal N(0,1)}
\left[
\frac{
\beta_t^2
}{
2\sigma_t^2\alpha_t(1-\bar\alpha_t)
}
\left(
\varepsilon_t-\varepsilon_\theta(X_t,t)
\right)^2
\right]
+
C_t ,\quad C_t
=
\log
\frac{\sigma_t}{\sqrt{\tilde\beta_t}}
+
\frac{\tilde\beta_t}{2\sigma_t^2}
-\frac12
\end{aligned}
```

Because $`X_t`$ is determined by $`\varepsilon_t`$ and $`x_0`$, once the expectation is explicitly taken over $`\varepsilon_t`$, we no longer need to write $`X_t\sim Q_t(\cdot\mid x_0)`$ separately. During optimization, constants can be omitted, so $`L_{t-1}`$ is equivalent to:

```math
L_{t-1}'=\mathbb E_{\varepsilon_t\sim\mathcal N(0,1)}
\left[
\frac{
\beta_t^2
}{
2\sigma_t^2\alpha_t(1-\bar\alpha_t)
}
\left(
\varepsilon_t-\varepsilon_\theta(X_t,t)
\right)^2
\right]
```

Substituting $`X_t= \sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0+\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\varepsilon_t`$ gives:

```math
L_{t-1}'=\mathbb E_{\varepsilon_t\sim\mathcal N(0,1)}
\left[
\frac{
\beta_t^2
}{
2\sigma_t^2\alpha_t(1-\bar\alpha_t)
}
\left(
\varepsilon_t-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0+\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\varepsilon_t,t)
\right)^2
\right]
```

Next, consider the following term in $`\mathcal L_{\mathrm{VLB}}`$:

```math
L_T=D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_T(\cdot\mid x_0)
\|
P_T,\quad P_T=\mathcal L(X_T)
\right)
```

where:

```math
\begin{aligned}
P_T&=\mathcal N(0,1)
\\Q_T(\cdot\mid x_0)
&=
\mathcal N
\left(
\sqrt{\bar\alpha_T}x_0,
1-\bar\alpha_T
\right)
\end{aligned}
```

Since both distributions can be computed directly,

```math
D_{\mathrm{KL}}
\left(
Q_T(\cdot\mid x_0)
\|
P_T
\right)
```

can be computed directly and is independent of the neural network. The middle terms require the neural network because they contain the intractable $`p_{t-1}`$. Therefore, this term can be ignored during optimization. Next, consider the following term in $`\mathcal L_{\mathrm{VLB}}`$:

```math
L_0=-\mathbb{E}_{X_1\sim Q_1(\cdot\mid x_0)}
\left[
\log p_0(x_0\mid X_1)
\right]
```

where:

```math
\begin{aligned}
p_0(x_0\mid x_1)&=\mathcal{N}\left( x_0;\mu_\theta(x_1, 1), \sigma^2_1 \right)
\\\mu_\theta(X_1,1)&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\alpha_1}}
\left(
X_1
-
\frac{\beta_1}{\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_1}}
\varepsilon_\theta(X_1,1)
\right)
\end{aligned}
```

Substitute

```math
X_1
=
\sqrt{\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\varepsilon_1
```

to obtain:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\mu_\theta(X_1,1)&=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\alpha_1}}
\left(
\sqrt{\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\varepsilon_1
-
\frac{\beta_1}{\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_1}}
\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\varepsilon_1,1)
\right)
\
\\&=x_0+\sqrt{\frac{\beta_1}{\alpha_1}}\varepsilon_1-\frac{\beta_1}{\sqrt{\alpha_1-\alpha_1^2}}\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\varepsilon_1,1)
\\&=x_0+\sqrt{\frac{\beta_1}{\alpha_1}}\left(\varepsilon_1-\frac{\sqrt{\beta_1}}{\sqrt{1-\alpha_1}}\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\varepsilon_1,1)\right)
\\&=x_0+\sqrt{\frac{\beta_1}{\alpha_1}}\left(\varepsilon_1-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\varepsilon_1,1)\right)\quad (\frac{\sqrt{\beta_1}}{\sqrt{1-\alpha_1}}=1)
\end{aligned}
```

Thus:

```math
\begin{aligned}
L_0(x_0)
&= \mathbb{E}_{X_1\sim Q_1(\cdot\mid x_0)}
   \left[ -\log \mathcal{N}\!\left( x_0; \mu_\theta(X_1,1), \sigma_1^2 \right) \right] \\[4pt]
&= \mathbb{E}_{X_1\sim Q_1(\cdot\mid x_0)}
   \left[ -\log \left( \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_1^2}}
          \exp\!\left( -\frac{(x_0-\mu_\theta(X_1,1))^2}{2\sigma_1^2} \right) \right) \right] \\[4pt]
&= \mathbb{E}_{X_1\sim Q_1(\cdot\mid x_0)}
   \left[ -\log \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_1^2}}
          - \log \exp\!\left( -\frac{(x_0-\mu_\theta(X_1,1))^2}{2\sigma_1^2} \right) \right] \\[4pt]
&= \mathbb{E}_{X_1\sim Q_1(\cdot\mid x_0)}
   \left[ \frac{1}{2}\log(2\pi\sigma_1^2)
          - \left( -\frac{(x_0-\mu_\theta(X_1,1))^2}{2\sigma_1^2} \right) \right] \\[4pt]
&= \mathbb{E}_{X_1\sim Q_1(\cdot\mid x_0)}
   \left[ \frac{1}{2}\log(2\pi\sigma_1^2)
          + \frac{(x_0-\mu_\theta(X_1,1))^2}{2\sigma_1^2} \right]\\[4pt]
&= \mathbb{E}_{\varepsilon_1\sim \mathcal N(0,1)}
   \left[ \frac{1}{2}\log(2\pi\sigma_1^2)
          + \frac{\left(\sqrt{\frac{\beta_1}{\alpha_1}}\left(\varepsilon_1-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\varepsilon_1,1)\right)\right)^2}{2\sigma_1^2} \right]\\[4pt]
&= \mathbb{E}_{\varepsilon_1\sim \mathcal N(0,1)}
   \left[ \frac{1}{2}\log(2\pi\sigma_1^2)
          + \frac{\beta_1\left(\varepsilon_1-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\varepsilon_1,1)\right)^2}{2\alpha_1\sigma_1^2} \right]
\end{aligned}
```

In machine learning and mathematics, $`\log`$ usually denotes the natural logarithm with base $`e`$. Therefore, $`\log\exp\!\left( -\frac{(x_0-\mu_\theta(X_1,1))^2}{2\sigma_1^2} \right)=\! -\frac{(x_0-\mu_\theta(X_1,1))^2}{2\sigma_1^2}`$. During optimization, constants can be ignored, so $`L_0`$ is equivalent to:

```math
\begin{aligned}
L_0'
&=
\mathbb E_{\varepsilon_1\sim\mathcal N(0,1)}
\left[\frac{\beta_1\left(\varepsilon_1-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{\beta_1}\varepsilon_1,1)\right)^2}{2\alpha_1\sigma_1^2}
\right]
\\&=\mathbb E_{\varepsilon_1\sim\mathcal N(0,1)}
\left[\frac{\beta_1\left(\varepsilon_1-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\bar\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_1}\varepsilon_1,1)\right)^2}{2\alpha_1\sigma_1^2}
\right],\quad \alpha_t= 1-\beta_t,\, \bar{\alpha}_t = \prod_{i=1}^t \alpha_i
\end{aligned}
```

Therefore, optimizing the full $`\mathcal L_{\mathrm{VLB}}`$ is equivalent to optimizing:

```math
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal L_{\mathrm{VLB}}&=L_0'+\sum_{t=2}^{T}L_{t-1}'
\\&=\mathbb E_{\varepsilon_1\sim\mathcal N(0,1)}
\left[\frac{\beta_1}{2\alpha_1\sigma_1^2}\left(\varepsilon_1-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\bar\alpha_1}x_0
+
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_1}\varepsilon_1,1)\right)^2\right]
\\&+\sum_{t=2}^T \mathbb E_{\varepsilon_t\sim\mathcal N(0,1)}
\left[
\frac{
\beta_t^2
}{
2\sigma_t^2\alpha_t(1-\bar\alpha_t)
}
\left(
\varepsilon_t-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0+\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\varepsilon_t,t)
\right)^2
\right]
\end{aligned}
```

However, in DDPM practice, it was found that if the complex weights in $`L_t'`$ are removed and $`L_0'`$ is also unified into the same form, then optimizing the following simplified loss function produces better sample quality:

```math
L_{\mathrm{simple}}
=\sum_{t=1}^T
\mathbb E_{\varepsilon\sim \mathcal N(0,1)}
\left[
\left(
\varepsilon-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0
+
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\varepsilon,t)
\right)^2
\right]
```

Multiplying by the constant $`\frac{1}{T}`$ does not affect the optimization:

```math
\begin{aligned}
L_{\mathrm{simple}}
&=\sum_{t=1}^T\frac{1}{T}
\mathbb E_{\varepsilon\sim \mathcal N(0,1)}
\left[
\left(
\varepsilon-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0
+
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\varepsilon,t)
\right)^2
\right]
\\
&=\mathbb E_{t\sim \text{Uniform}(\{1,\cdots,T\})}\left[\mathbb E_{\varepsilon\sim \mathcal N(0,1)}
\left[
\left(
\varepsilon-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0
+
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\varepsilon,t)
\right)^2
\right]\right]
\\
&=\mathbb E_{\varepsilon\sim \mathcal N(0,1),t\sim \text{Uniform}(\{1,\cdots,T\})}
\left[
\left(
\varepsilon-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0
+
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\varepsilon,t)
\right)^2
\right]
\end{aligned}
```

Here, $`\text{Uniform}(\{1,\cdots,T\})`$ denotes the uniform distribution. When the training set contains only $`x_0`$, the training data distribution is $`\mathcal N(x_0,0)`$. We randomly sample $`t`$ and $`\epsilon`$, and compute:

```math
x_t=\sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0
+
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\epsilon
```

Then we feed $`x_t,t`$ into the neural network $`\theta`$ and obtain the output $`\epsilon_\theta`$. At this point, we have all the data needed for stochastic gradient descent. We repeat this process until training ends. During generation, we feed $`x_t,t`$ into the neural network $`\theta`$ and obtain $`\epsilon_\theta`$. Then, using:

```math
\mu_\theta(x_t,t)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{\alpha_t}}
\left(
x_t
-
\frac{\beta_t}{\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}}
\varepsilon_\theta(x_t,t)
\right)
```

we can compute $`\mu_\theta`$. Finally, according to:

```math
p_{t-1}(x_{t-1}\mid x_t)=\mathcal{N}\left( x_{t-1};
\mu_\theta(x_t,t), \sigma^2_t\right)
```

we obtain the distribution for generating $`x_{t-1}`$. Repeating this process eventually gives the distribution of the generated $`x_0`$. Since the distribution of $`x_0`$ is $`\mathcal N(x_0,0)`$, the distribution of the generated $`x_0`$ given by the neural network will also be approximately $`\mathcal N(x_0,0)`$. Suppose now we have a $`64*64*3`$ image and flatten it into $`x_0\in \mathbb R^{64*64*3}`$. We also extend $`\varepsilon`$ to $`\varepsilon\in \mathbb R^{64*64*3}`$. Then the loss function becomes:

```math
L_{\mathrm{simple}}=\mathbb E_{\varepsilon\sim \mathcal N(0,\mathbf I),t\sim \text{Uniform}(\{1,\cdots,T\})}
\left[
\|
\varepsilon-\varepsilon_\theta(\sqrt{\bar\alpha_t}x_0
+
\sqrt{1-\bar\alpha_t}\varepsilon,t)
\|^2
\right]
```

By optimizing this loss function, the neural network learns to generate images.

